title: For Sale:  Colt Diamondback 22lr 6" in Nickel
location: Cary, NC, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have a very nice Colt Diamondback 22lr 6" in Nickel.  This is part of my father's collection that he passed on to me.  I have the box, documentation, and original purchase receipts.  I am not an avid collector, but based on the rating guide in the Blue Book this is 98+%.  Only visible flaws are the "drag lines" of the barrel being revolved in handling, and a handful of very very minor scratch / scuffs, mostly on the right side of the barrel and one tiny mark on the left side.  You may barely be able to make them out in the pictures.  Consistent with a gun that has been just lovingly handled a dozen or so times over the last 30 years for inspections and cleanings.  Is this “mint” or “excellent”?  I’m not sure but it’s a damn pretty gun.  One of only 2200 manufactured according to my research.

I am not aware of it ever having been fired, but I believe that it has at least had some test shots fired through it (I took it for an evaluation at a gun shop years ago and they confirmed it has been fired).  I have had it for about 15 years and aside from admiring it once in a while have never fired it.  Stored always in a padded case inside an air conditioned environment.  It's really a beautiful gun.  

It appears that prices are “skyrocketing” (if you believe the posts) but I am offering this at ½ way between 98% ($2350) and 100% ($2650) of the BlueBook value, which appears to be “behind” on value.  I really hope someone will enjoy adding this to their collection.

I'm in Cary, North Carolina and can be reached at REDACTED or REDACTED.  I would strongly prefer a local sale.

Beretta ARX 100 223 Rem 556NATO 16" Black Side Folding 30Rd Flip Up Front and Rear JXR11B00
 Beretta is shipping the ARX 100 in 5.56. This is the civilian version of a battle rifle that’s currently in service in Italy and a handful of other countries. The rifle combines the operational familiarity of both the AR-15 platform and the AK platform into a versatile rifle that’s built for active service. Every detail of the gun is adaptable. Controls can be switched easily, without tools. Even the various calibers of barrels are interchangeable, on the fly. It is an impressive rifle. Beretta is calling the ARX 100 “The Ultimate Tactical Rifle.” 
Beretta ARX100! This model is chambered for 5.56/.223. It is a piston operated rifle, this means less maintenance and incredible reliability. The ARX100 was engineered with one purpose in mind: to be today’s best tactical semiauto rifle. It takes the concept of a modular rifle to futuristic levels, while maintaining an absolutely simple operation that make it ultra-reliable. With ambidextrous controls, easily-replaceable barrel and virtually endless possibilities for customization and accessorization, the ARX100 is adaptable to any firing scenario and is perfect for today’s most demanding tactical shooter. Ultimate Reliability and Ease of Maintenance The ARX100 features a constant contact/short-stroke gas piston system that makes it feed and fire under the most unforgiving conditions. The lightweight technopolymer receiver allows for reliable operation with virtually no lubricants. To make maintenance easy and trouble-free, this rifle has no pins and can be completely disassembled in a matter of seconds with no tools at all. Ultimate Versatility This rifle was designed to be completely ambidextrous, and all the critical controls on it may be operated right- or left-handed. These include the 2-position safety, the magazine release, the bolt release and charging handle and the case-ejection selector, which determines whether spent brass is ejected to the right or left. The flip-up backup sights that come standard on the ARX100 are also versatile, offering an easily-adjustable diopter system ranged from 100 to 800 yards. The barrel is also easily replaceable in seconds, making is possible to use different lengths and calibers without any tools required. Lastly, the folding stock is adjustable for length of pull at the touch of a button, using a simple and rugged telescopic construction. Ultimate Accessorization The possibilities for accessorization on the ARX100 are limited only by the user’s imagination. It comes out of the box with a full-length Picatinny rail on top, which is perfect for attaching a variety of optics and other sighting systems. It also has Picatinny rails on both sides of and under the fore-end, which offer countless possibilities for easily adding lighting systems and other tactical devices. title: For Sale/Trade:  **FRIDAY ONLY**1911 Military Package
postcontent:
Friday evening/night only in or around the Madison area!  If you want it but can't meet on Friday, you'll need to come out near Milwuakee to pick it up.

Shooters Arms Manufacturing (SAM) M1911 Military. Full size 1911 with one 8-round magazine ($550), one 7-round Colt factory magazine ($35 - not pictured), WRB XMH holster with thumb break and magazine pouch ($30 - not pictured), zippered locking soft case ($19), rubber Hogue grips with finger grooves ($20), wood Hogue Sig Sauer grips ($50), 8 brand new 16 lb recoil springs ($75), a used .45 caliber cleaning kit ($12), 20 rounds of Federal Premium low recoil Hydra Shok ammo ($28), and an antique leather shoulder holster with built-in spring retention ($?).

I've put exactly 132 rounds through the pistol. The previous owner bought it and kept it new, but there's a little surface rust in the grip screw heads from replacing the grips. He also apparently dropped it so there's a ding on the front left side of the slide, and the left corner of the hammer and safety. Nothing which affects the mechanics of this gun. This is considered one of the best entry-level 1911's, and shoots excellent. Perfect if you're trying to decide if you want to go a 1911 route without paying for an expensive name, or looking for a project gun to test your gunsmithing skills on (not that it needs anything).

The previous owner told me the leather shoulder holster is from WWII, but there's no markings. It's in pretty rough shape. The holster needs some stitching and the shoulder strap is cracking or split in several places.

Price shown is for cash - trade value will be a little higher. I know funds are pretty tight for a lot of us right now, so while I prefer cash I'm open to trades, especially partial trades with a bit of cash. I would rather add ammo, mags, etc instead of cash if you have something I want that's worth significantly more, but I do have a little cash if needed for the perfect trade.

Do NOT ask what my bottom dollar is or if I still have this - I won't respond. And please don't send me any truly insulting offers. It's not a must-sell situation and I'm perfectly happy keeping this around, just looking for something I would use more, or a little cash for the kitty. Otherwise feel free to ask any questions you may have.

At Gander Mountain: http://www.gandermountain.com/modperl/product/details.cgi?i=729306

Specs: http://www.shootersarms.com.ph/firearms_detail.php?id=6.

title: For Sale/Trade:  PSA Amended
location: Right outside of Camden, Dayton, Ohio
postcontent:
Sent to the anonymous purveyor of the following ad at eleven forty P.M. (EDT) on the eighteenth of September, 2014 -

(http://www.armslist.com/posts/3510158/dayton-ohio-services-want-to-buy--public-service-announcement)

"There is a moron on here that thinks people will pay him to take their guns. Not only has he posted wondering why people will not give guns away for free but he keeps reposting the ad! After speaking with the man, he does not seem sane enough to even be able to own a firearm. Please help me keep idiots like this off the page by flagging it everytime it's posted (SIC)."

(The message is as follows -) Now you're clearly misinterpreting the individual's postings. I just hope that, for the sake of everyone, it's not being done with intent. Frankly, I agree with the user, who's posts I've come across twice now and who's posts have maintained roughly the same message - 'We don't give guns away for free.' Again, what you're either failing to comprehend or what has upset you; what the individual is trying to express is that, I'm not going to give you my firearm for nothing and you're certainly not going to give me yours.

I've been having to deal with all of the crooked, 'let's trade up' or 'this may be what I have and it may not' or 'how about you pay me more than retail for what I've done mishandled for years' or 'good luck after dealing with me,' backdoor dealers and wannabe salesmen and bamboozlers for some time now; and I have to say - there's a lot more bad to be found out there than good. I've been lied to in some shape or form, swindled and sold lemons on almost every single occasion. I've been ill-informed regarding chamberings. I've been sold 'like new in box' firearms that do not function. I've been on my way to meet people that I've never heard from again. I've had firearms blatantly sold out from under me. I've even been lied to about damages seen in pictures that supposedly didn't exist upon 'mint condition' handguns, where I've made the decision to purchase anyway after making the drive, and have got the proof that says otherwise on my hip - the proof that every abrasion, pitting and loss of finish pictured in the conveniently piss-grade photos is in fact not just a product of someone's new, unwieldy camera phone. Of course everyone wants to meet you in the parking lots of Wal-Mart or McDonald's (which I'm not sure isn't an infraction of the law) after dark, so you're surely not going to be testing anything out.

It would appear that the second market firearms trade is a niche that anyone looking to make a dishonest buck can get into. You really have to watch your back when it comes to laying your cards down against those who have no credentials to speak off and are only bonded by bullshit, i.e. your everyday wheeler dealer.

So with that being said, and in the name of dispelling your wild assertion as well as clearing up any further confusion on the behalf of others, I have to ask: exactly why wouldn't an honest individual stand up for his fellow enthusiasts by posing a question such as this? Furthermore, exactly what legitimate purpose is supposedly served by 'fishing in the dark,' as it is, seemingly looking to draw in and capitalize on the naive and uninformed? Or rather, as the person on trial so put it, "Why is it when people post items for free, (and) you respond agreeing with their price
and even agree to pick it up, they go all ballistic on you? Don't put free if it's not free."

Personally, I believe that a mandate requiring the inclusion of either an asking price, the fare allocated or at least an estimated value in each and every listing would better serve us all. Thank you for your time.

  Archie M. Leedle II

title: For Sale/Trade:  PSA Amended
location: Right outside of Camden, Cincinnati, Ohio
postcontent:
Sent to the anonymous purveyor of the following ad at eleven forty P.M. (EDT) on the eighteenth of September, 2014 -

(http://www.armslist.com/posts/3510158/dayton-ohio-services-want-to-buy--public-service-announcement)

"There is a moron on here that thinks people will pay him to take their guns. Not only has he posted wondering why people will not give guns away for free but he keeps reposting the ad! After speaking with the man, he does not seem sane enough to even be able to own a firearm. Please help me keep idiots like this off the page by flagging it everytime it's posted (SIC)."

(The message is as follows -) Now you're clearly misinterpreting the individual's postings. I just hope that, for the sake of everyone, it's not being done with intent. Frankly, I agree with the user, who's posts I've come across twice now and who's posts have maintained roughly the same message - 'We don't give guns away for free.' Again, what you're either failing to comprehend or what has upset you; what the individual is trying to express is that, I'm not going to give you my firearm for nothing and you're certainly not going to give me yours.

I've been having to deal with all of the crooked, 'let's trade up' or 'this may be what I have and it may not' or 'how about you pay me more than retail for what I've done mishandled for years' or 'good luck after dealing with me,' backdoor dealers and wannabe salesmen and bamboozlers for some time now; and I have to say - there's a lot more bad to be found out there than good. I've been lied to in some shape or form, swindled and sold lemons on almost every single occasion. I've been ill-informed regarding chamberings. I've been sold 'like new in box' firearms that do not function. I've been on my way to meet people that I've never heard from again. I've had firearms blatantly sold out from under me. I've even been lied to about damages seen in pictures that supposedly didn't exist upon 'mint condition' handguns, where I've made the decision to purchase anyway after making the drive, and have got the proof that says otherwise on my hip - the proof that every abrasion, pitting and loss of finish pictured in the conveniently piss-grade photos is in fact not just a product of someone's new, unwieldy camera phone. Of course everyone wants to meet you in the parking lots of Wal-Mart or McDonald's (which I'm not sure isn't an infraction of the law) after dark, so you're surely not going to be testing anything out.

It would appear that the second market firearms trade is a niche that anyone looking to make a dishonest buck can get into. You really have to watch your back when it comes to laying your cards down against those who have no credentials to speak off and are only bonded by bullshit, i.e. your everyday wheeler dealer.

So with that being said, and in the name of dispelling your wild assertion as well as clearing up any further confusion on the behalf of others, I have to ask: exactly why wouldn't an honest individual stand up for his fellow enthusiasts by posing a question such as this? Furthermore, exactly what legitimate purpose is supposedly served by 'fishing in the dark,' as it is, seemingly looking to draw in and capitalize on the naive and uninformed? Or rather, as the person on trial so put it, "Why is it when people post items for free, (and) you respond agreeing with their price
and even agree to pick it up, they go all ballistic on you? Don't put free if it's not free."

Personally, I believe that a mandate requiring the inclusion of either an asking price, the fare allocated or at least an estimated value in each and every listing would better serve us all. Thank you for your time.

  Archie M. Leedle II
